{
  "answer": "**The couplet you're referring to is the opening *sher* (couplet) of Ghalib's ghazal numbered 153 in the *Diwan-e-Ghalib*.**\n\nThe original Urdu is:  \n**नक्श़ फ़र्यादि है किस की शोख़ी‐ए तहरीर का  \nक़ाग़ज़ की पोसतीन पहने हर फ़िग़र है शिक़वा**[^1]\n\nIn English translation:  \n**Whose playful script does this whole painted world complain of?**  \n**Each figure wears the paper robes a petitioner is made of.**[^1]\n\nHere, *naqsh faryadi* (\"the image/figure complains\" or \"the drawing is the complainant\") refers to the painted or drawn figures protesting (*shikwa* or *faryad*) the *shokhi-e-tehreer* (\"mischief/playfulness of the writing/pen/artist's hand\"). Even the figures on a mere sheet of paper (*kaghaz ki postin*, \"paper garment/robe\") become petitioners against the artist's capricious strokes.[^1]\n\nThis ghazal explores themes of creation, illusion, and existential complaint through the metaphor of painting or calligraphy bringing figures to life only to make them lament their existence.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/153-naqsh-faryadi-hai-kis-ki-shokhi-e-tehreer-ka/translation/#p-0e42b0).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 153 (\"Naqsh faryadi hai kis ki shokhi-e-tehreer ka\"), [full chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/153-naqsh-faryadi-hai-kis-ki-shokhi-e-tehreer-ka/translation/).",
